# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: deception-technology-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] A **canary trap** is a method for exposing an information leak by giving different versions of a sensitive document to each of several suspects and seeing which version gets leaked.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] It could be one false statement, to see whether sensitive information gets out to other people as well.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] Special attention is paid to the quality of the prose of the unique language, in the hopes that the suspect will repeat it verbatim in the leak, thereby identifying the version of the document.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] The term was coined by Tom Clancy in his 1987 novel *Patriot Games*, although Clancy did not invent the technique.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] The actual method (usually referred to as a **barium meal test** in espionage circles) has been used by intelligence agencies for many years.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] A refinement of this technique uses a thesaurus program to shuffle through synonyms, thus making every copy of the document unique.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] According to the book *Spycatcher* by Peter Wright (published in 1987), the technique is standard practice that has been used by MI5 (and other intelligence agencies) for many years, under the name "barium meal test", named after the medical procedure.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] A barium meal test is flexible and may take many different forms.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] The basic premise is to reveal a supposed secret to a suspected enemy (but nobody else) then monitor whether there is evidence of the fake information being utilized by the other side.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] For example, a suspected double agent could be offered some tempting "bait": e.g., be told that important information was stored at a dead drop site.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] The fake dead drop site could then be periodically checked for signs of disturbance.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] If the site showed signs of being disturbed (for instance, in order to copy microfilm stored there), then this would confirm that the suspected enemy really was an enemy, i.e., a double agent.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] Following the troubled production of *Star Trek: The Motion Picture* in the late 1970s, Paramount Pictures effectively replaced Gene Roddenberry as producer of further movies in the franchise with Harve Bennett.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] Roddenberry was retained as an "executive consultant", due to the high regard the series' fans held him in; while he had little real authority he was still kept involved in the creative process.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] The fans often complained about particular plot developments proposed for the films, such as the death of Spock in *Star Trek II*, that Roddenberry had opposed.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] So, before any drafts of the screenplay for *Star Trek III: The Search for Spock* were circulated, Bennett arranged for each individual copy to have subtle clues distinguishing it from the others.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] Shortly after Roddenberry opposed the destruction of the *Enterprise* at the climax of that film, fans began to complain to Paramount and Bennett.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] He found that a leaked copy of the script was the one given to Roddenberry, but was unable to do anything about it.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] After a series of leaks at Tesla Motors in 2008, CEO Elon Musk reportedly sent slightly different versions of an e-mail to each employee in an attempt to reveal potential leakers.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] The e-mail was disguised as a request to employees to sign a new non-disclosure agreement.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] The plan was undermined when the company's general counsel forwarded his own unique version of the e-mail with the attached agreement.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] As a result, Musk's scheme was realized by employees who now had a safe copy to leak.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] In October 2019, British celebrity Coleen Rooney used a barium meal test to identify who was leaking information from her private Instagram stories to tabloid newspaper *The Sun* by posting fake stories which were blocked to all but one account.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] When these details appeared in the press, she publicly identified the leaks as coming from the account of Rebekah Vardy, wife of soccer player Jamie Vardy.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] The subsequent libel trial became known as the Wagatha Christie case.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] In December 2020, Andrew Lewer, a Member of Parliament and parliamentary private secretary in the UK government, was fired from his latter post after a canary trap in the form of a letter reminding staff not to leak was published on the website *Guido Fawkes*.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] In 2023, Apple Inc. fired a staffer for leaking information regarding upcoming software releases; emails regarding the release date were sent to various employees containing dates for different releases in unique combinations to identify the source of the leaked information.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] In 2025, it was reported that a candidate for a senior position within Britain's external intelligence agency, MI6, was able to infer a leak within the United Kingdom Security Vetting agency using the barium meal technique.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] In 2026, an Albertan separatist group gained illegitimate access to the Alberta electoral database.
[src:deception-technology-deep/canary-trap] Using a canary trap, it was found that the Republican Party of Alberta had leaked the data to the group.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Deception technology considers the point of view of human attackers and method for exploiting and navigating networks to identify and exfiltrate data.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] It integrates with existing technologies to provide new visibility into the internal networks, share high probability alerts and threat intelligence with the existing infrastructure.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Deception technology automates the creation of traps (decoys) and lures, which are strategically integrated among existing IT resources.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] These decoys provide an additional layer of protection to thwart attackers who have breached the network.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Traps can be IT assets that utilize genuine licensed operating system software or emulate various devices, such as medical devices, automated teller machines (ATMs), retail point-of-sale systems, switches, routers, and more.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] On the other hand, lures typically consist of real information technology resources, such as files of different types, that are placed on actual IT assets.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Due to advancement in the area of cybersecurity, deception technology programs are increasingly proactive in approach and produce fewer false-positive alerts.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] The goal is to accurately discover the intention of the attacker and their tactics, technique and procedure.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] These information will enable effective response from the deception technology platforms.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Upon penetrating the network, attackers seek to establish a backdoor and then use this to identify and exfiltrate data and intellectual property.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] They begin moving laterally through the internal VLANs and almost immediately will "encounter" one of the traps.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Interacting with one of these "decoys" will trigger an alert.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] These alerts have very high probability and almost always coincide to an ongoing attack.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] The deception is designed to lure the attacker in – the attacker may consider this a worthy asset and continue by injecting malware.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Deception technology generally allows for automated static and dynamic analysis of this injected malware and provides these reports through automation to the security operations personnel.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Deception technology may also identify, through indicators of compromise (IOC), suspect end-points that are part of the compromise cycle.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Automation also allows for an automated memory analysis of the suspect endpoints, and then automatically isolating the suspect endpoints.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Internet of things (IoT) devices are not usually scanned by legacy defense in depth and remain prime targets for attackers within the network.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Deception technology can identify attackers moving laterally into the network within these devices.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Integrated turnkey devices that utilize embedded operating systems but do not allow these operating systems to be scanned or closely protected by embedded end-point or intrusion detection software are also well protected by a deception technology deployment in the same network.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Examples include process control systems (SCADA) used in many manufacturing applications on a global basis.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Deception technology has been associated with the discovery of Zombie Zero, an attack vector.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Deception technology identified this attacker utilizing malware embedded in barcode readers which were manufactured overseas.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Medical devices are particular vulnerable to cyber-attacks within the healthcare networks.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] As FDA-certified devices, they are in closed systems and not accessible to standard cyber defense software.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Deception technology can surround and protect these devices and identify attackers using backdoor placement and data exfiltration.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Recent documented cyber attacks on medical devices include x-ray machines, CT scanners, MRI scanners, blood gas analyzers, PACS systems and many more.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Networks utilizing these devices can be protected by deception technology.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] This attack vector, called medical device hijack or medjack, is estimated to have penetrated many hospitals worldwide.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Specialized deception technology products are now capable of addressing the rise in ransomware by deceiving ransomware into engaging in an attack on a decoy resource, while isolating the infection points and alerting the cyber defense software team.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Honeypots were perhaps the first very simple form of deception.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] A honeypot appeared simply as an unprotected information technology resource and presented itself in an attractive way to a prospective attacker already within the network.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] However, most early honeypots exhibit challenges with functionality, integrity and overall efficacy in meeting these goals.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] A key difficulty was lack of automation that enabled broad scale deployment; a deployment strategy that aimed to cover an enterprise where up to tens of thousands of VLANS needed to be protected would not be economically efficient using manual processes and manual configuration.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] The gap between legacy honeypots and modern deception technology has diminished over time and will continue to do so.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Modern honeypots constitute the low end of the deception technology space today.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Traditional cyber defense technologies such as firewalls and endpoint security seek primarily to defend a perimeter, but they cannot do so with 100% certainty.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Heuristics may find an attacker within the network, but often generate so many alerts that critical alerts are missed.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] In a large enterprise, the alert volume may reach millions of alerts per day.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Security operations personnel cannot process most of the activity easily, yet it only takes one successful penetration to compromise an entire network.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] This means cyber-attackers can penetrate these networks and move unimpeded for months, stealing data and intellectual property.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Deception technology produces alerts that are the end product of a binary process.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Probability is essentially reduced to two values: 0% and 100%.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Any party that seeks to identify, ping, enter, view any trap or utilizes a lure is immediately identified as malicious by this behavior because anyone touching these traps or lures should not be doing so.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] This certainty is an advantage over the many extraneous alerts generated by heuristics and probability-based.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Best practice shows that deception technology is not a stand-alone strategy.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Deception technology is an additional compatible layer to the existing defense-in-depth cyber defense.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] Partner integrations make it most useful.
[src:deception-technology-deep/deception-technology] The goal is to add protection for the most advanced and sophisticated human attackers that will successfully penetrate the perimeter.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] In computer terminology, a **honeypot** is a computer security mechanism set to detect, deflect, or, in some manner, counteract attempts at unauthorized use of information systems.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Generally, a honeypot consists of data (for example, in a network site) that appears to be a legitimate part of the site which contains information or resources of value to attackers.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] It is actually isolated, monitored, and capable of blocking or analyzing the attackers.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] This is similar to police sting operations, colloquially known as "baiting" a suspect.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] The main use for this network decoy is to distract potential attackers from more important information and machines on the real network, learn about the forms of attacks they can suffer, and examine such attacks during and after the exploitation of a honeypot.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] It provides a way to prevent and see vulnerabilities in a specific network system.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] A honeypot is a decoy used to protect a network from present or future attacks.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Honeypots derive their value from the use by attackers.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] If not interacted with, the honeypot has little to no value.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Honeypots can be used for everything from slowing down or stopping automated attacks, capturing new exploits, to gathering intelligence on emerging threats or early warning and prediction.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Honeypots can be classified based on their deployment (use/action) and based on their level of involvement.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Recently, a new market segment called deception technology has emerged using basic honeypot technology with the addition of advanced automation for scale.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Deception technology addresses the automated deployment of honeypot resources over a large commercial enterprise or government institution.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] A malware honeypot is a decoy designed to intentionally attract malicious software.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] It does this by imitating a vulnerable system or network, such as a web server.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] The honeypot is intentionally set up with security flaws that look to invite these malware attacks.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Once attacked, IT teams can then analyze the malware to better understand where it comes from and how it acts.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Spammers abuse vulnerable resources such as open mail relays and open proxies.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] These are servers that accept e-mail from anyone on the Internet—including spammers—and send it to its destination.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Some system administrators have created honeypot programs that masquerade as these abusable resources to discover spammer activity.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] There are several capabilities such honeypots provide to these administrators, and the existence of such fake abusable systems makes abuse more difficult or risky.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Honeypots can be a powerful countermeasure to abuse from those who rely on very high-volume abuse (e.g., spammers).
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] These honeypots can reveal the abuser's IP address and provide bulk spam capture (which enables operators to determine spammers' URLs and response mechanisms).
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] The apparent source may be another abused system.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Spammers and other abusers may use a chain of such abused systems to make detection of the original starting point of the abuse traffic difficult.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] This in itself is indicative of the power of honeypots as anti-spam tools.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] In the early days of anti-spam honeypots, spammers, with little concern for hiding their location, felt safe testing for vulnerabilities and sending spam directly from their own systems.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Honeypots made the abuse riskier and more difficult.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Spam still flows through open relays, but the volume is much smaller than in 2001-02.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] While most spam originates in the U.S., spammers hop through open relays across political boundaries to mask their origin.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Honeypot operators may use intercepted relay tests to recognize and thwart attempts to relay spam through their honeypots.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] "Thwart" may mean "accept the relay spam but decline to deliver it." Honeypot operators may discover other details concerning the spam and the spammer by examining the captured spam messages.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Open-relay honeypots include Jackpot, written in Java by Jack Cleaver; *smtpot.py*, written in Python by Karl A.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] The *Bubblegum Proxypot* is an open-source honeypot (or "proxypot").
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] An email address that is not used for any other purpose than to receive spam can also be considered a spam honeypot.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Compared with the term "spamtrap", the term "honeypot" might be more suitable for systems and techniques that are used to detect or counterattack probes.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] With a spamtrap, spam arrives at its destination "legitimately"—exactly as non-spam email would arrive.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] An amalgam of these techniques is Project Honey Pot, a distributed, open-source project that uses honeypot pages installed on websites around the world.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] These honeypot pages disseminate uniquely tagged spamtrap email addresses and spammers can then be tracked—the corresponding spam mail is subsequently sent to these spamtrap e-mail addresses.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Databases often get attacked by intruders using SQL injection.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] As such activities are not recognized by basic firewalls, companies often use database firewalls for protection.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Some of the available SQL database firewalls provide/support honeypot architectures so that the intruder runs against a trap database while the web application remains functional.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Industrial Control Systems (ICS) are often the target of cyberattacks.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] One of the main targets within ICS are Programmable Logic Controllers.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] In order to understand intruders' techniques in this context, several honeypots have been proposed.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Conpot is a low interaction honeypot capable of simulation Siemens PLCs.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] HoneyPLC is a medium interaction honeypot that can simulate Siemens, Rockwell and other PLC brands.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Just as honeypots are weapons against spammers, honeypot detection systems are spammer-employed counter-weapons.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] This is an unusual circumstance in software; a situation in which "versionitis" (a large number of versions of the same software, all differing slightly from each other) can be beneficial.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] There's also an advantage in having some easy-to-detect honeypots deployed.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Fred Cohen, the inventor of the Deception Toolkit, argues that every system running his honeypot should have a deception port which adversaries can use to detect the honeypot.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Cohen believes that this might deter adversaries.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] The goal of honeypots is to attract and engage attackers for a sufficiently long period to obtain high-level Indicators of Compromise (IoC) such as attack tools and Tactics, Techniques, and Procedures (TTPs).
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Thus, a honeypot needs to emulate essential services in the production network and grant the attacker the freedom to perform adversarial activities to increase its attractiveness to the attacker.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Although the honeypot is a controlled environment and can be monitored by using tools such as honeywall, attackers may still be able to use some honeypots as pivot nodes to penetrate production systems.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] The second risk of honeypots is that they may attract legitimate users due to a lack of communication in large-scale enterprise networks.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] For example, the security team who applies and monitors the honeypot may not disclose the honeypot location to all users in time due to the lack of communication or the prevention of insider threats.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Two or more honeypots on a network form a *honey net*.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Typically, a honey net is used for monitoring a larger and/or more diverse network in which one honeypot may not be sufficient.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Honey nets and honeypots are usually implemented as parts of larger network intrusion detection systems.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] A *honey farm* is a centralized collection of honeypots and analysis tools.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] The concept of the honey net first began in 1999 when Lance Spitzner, founder of the Honeynet Project, published the paper "To Build a Honeypot".
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] An early formulation of the concept, called "entrapment", is defined in FIPS 39 (1976) as "the deliberate planting of apparent flaws in a system for the purpose of detecting attempted penetrations or confusing an intruder about which flaws to exploit".
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] The earliest honeypot techniques are described in Clifford Stoll's 1989 book *The Cuckoo's Egg*.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] One of the earliest documented cases of the cybersecurity use of a honeypot began in January 1991.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] On January 7, 1991, while he worked at AT&T Bell Laboratories Bill Cheswick observed a criminal hacker, known as a cracker, attempting to obtain a copy of a password file.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] Cheswick wrote that he and colleagues constructed a "chroot "Jail" (or "roach motel")" which allowed them to observe their attacker over a period of several months.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] In 2017, Dutch police used honeypot techniques to track down users of the darknet market Hansa.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] The metaphor of a bear being attracted to and stealing honey is common in many traditions, including Germanic, Celtic, and Slavic.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] A common Slavic word for the bear is *medved* "honey eater".
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeypot-computing] The tradition of bears stealing honey has been passed down through stories and folklore, especially the well known Winnie the Pooh.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeytoken] The uniqueness of honeytokens enables their use in an intrusion-detection system (IDS) as it searches for suspicious activity on a computer network, alerting the system administrator to things that would otherwise go unnoticed.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeytoken] While firewalls can only catch threats that have not yet entered a network, honeytokens can mark threats that slipped past a firewall.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeytoken] Honeytokens can be read by a reactive security mechanism to intercept malicious activity, e.g. by dropping packets at the router if they contain the honeytoken.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeytoken] However, such mechanisms have pitfalls; for example, if a honeytoken is poorly chosen so that it appears by chance in legitimate network traffic, those packets will be dropped too.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeytoken] In the field of computer security, **honeytokens** are honeypots that are not computer systems.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeytoken] Their value lies not in their use, but in their abuse.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeytoken] As such, they are a generalization of such ideas as the honeypot and the canary values often used in stack protection schemes.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeytoken] Honeytokens do not necessarily prevent tampering with the data, but instead give the administrator a further measure of confidence in the data integrity.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeytoken] The term was coined by Augusto Paes de Barros Friday, February 21st, 2003 via a message chain on Seclists.org.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeytoken] Honeytokens can exist in many forms, from a fake account to a database entry that would only be selected by malicious queries.
[src:deception-technology-deep/honeytoken] A particular example of a honeytoken is a fake email address inserted into a mailing list to track whether the list has been stolen.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] An **intrusion detection system** (**IDS**) is a device or software application that monitors a network or systems for malicious activity or policy violations.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Any intrusion activity or violation is typically either reported to an administrator or collected centrally using a security information and event management (SIEM) system.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] A SIEM system combines outputs from multiple sources and uses alarm filtering techniques to distinguish malicious activity from false alarms.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] IDS types range in scope from single computers to large networks.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The most common classifications are **network intrusion detection systems** (**NIDS**) and **host-based intrusion detection systems** (**HIDS**).
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] A system that monitors important operating system files is an example of an HIDS, while a system that analyzes incoming network traffic is an example of an NIDS.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] It is also possible to classify IDS by detection approach.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The most well-known variants are signature-based detection (recognizing bad patterns, such as exploitation attempts) and anomaly-based detection (detecting deviations from a model of "good" traffic, which often relies on machine learning).
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Another common variant is reputation-based detection (recognizing the potential threat according to the reputation scores).
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Some IDS products have the ability to respond to detected intrusions.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Systems with response capabilities are typically referred to as an **intrusion prevention system** (**IPS**).
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Intrusion detection systems can also serve specific purposes by augmenting them with custom tools, such as using a honeypot to attract and characterize malicious traffic.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Although they both relate to network security, an IDS differs from a firewall in that a conventional network firewall (distinct from a next-generation firewall) uses a static set of rules to permit or deny network connections.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] It implicitly prevents intrusions, assuming an appropriate set of rules have been defined.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Essentially, firewalls limit access between networks to prevent intrusion and do not signal an attack from inside the network.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] An IDS describes a suspected intrusion once it has taken place and signals an alarm.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] An IDS also watches for attacks that originate from within a system.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] This is traditionally achieved by examining network communications, identifying heuristics and patterns (often known as signatures) of common computer attacks, and taking action to alert operators.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] A system that terminates connections is called an intrusion prevention system, and performs access control like an application layer firewall.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] IDS can be classified by where detection takes place (network or host) or the detection method that is employed (signature or anomaly-based).
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Network intrusion detection systems (NIDS) are placed at a strategic point or points within the network to monitor traffic to and from all devices on the network.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] It performs an analysis of passing traffic on the entire subnet, and matches the traffic that is passed on the subnets to the library of known attacks.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Once an attack is identified, or abnormal behavior is sensed, the alert can be sent to the administrator.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] NIDS function to safeguard every device and the entire network from unauthorized access.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] An example of an NIDS would be installing it on the subnet where firewalls are located in order to see if someone is trying to break into the firewall.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Ideally one would scan all inbound and outbound traffic, however doing so might create a bottleneck that would impair the overall speed of the network.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] OPNET and NetSim are commonly used tools for simulating network intrusion detection systems.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] NID Systems are also capable of comparing signatures for similar packets to link and drop harmful detected packets which have a signature matching the records in the NIDS.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] When we classify the design of the NIDS according to the system interactivity property, there are two types: on-line and off-line NIDS, often referred to as inline and tap mode, respectively.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] On-line NIDS deals with the network in real time.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] It analyses the Ethernet packets and applies some rules, to decide if it is an attack or not.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Off-line NIDS deals with stored data and passes it through some processes to decide if it is an attack or not.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] NIDS can be also combined with other technologies to increase detection and prediction rates.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Artificial Neural Network (ANN) based IDS are capable of analyzing huge volumes of data due to the hidden layers and non-linear modeling, however this process requires time due its complex structure.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] This allows IDS to more efficiently recognize intrusion patterns.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Neural networks assist IDS in predicting attacks by learning from mistakes; ANN based IDS help develop an early warning system, based on two layers.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The first layer accepts single values, while the second layer takes the first's layers output as input; the cycle repeats and allows the system to automatically recognize new unforeseen patterns in the network.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] This system can average 99.9% detection and classification rate, based on research results of 24 network attacks, divided in four categories: DOS, Probe, Remote-to-Local, and user-to-root.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Host intrusion detection systems (HIDS) run on individual hosts or devices on the network.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] A HIDS monitors the inbound and outbound packets from the device only and will alert the user or administrator if suspicious activity is detected.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] It takes a snapshot of existing system files and matches it to the previous snapshot.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] If the critical system files were modified or deleted, an alert is sent to the administrator to investigate.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] An example of HIDS usage can be seen on mission critical machines, which are not expected to change their configurations.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Signature-based IDS is the detection of attacks by looking for specific patterns, such as byte sequences in network traffic, or known malicious instruction sequences used by malware.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] This terminology originates from anti-virus software, which refers to these detected patterns as signatures.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Although signature-based IDS can easily detect known attacks, it is difficult to detect new attacks, for which no pattern is available.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] In signature-based IDS, the signatures are released by a vendor for all its products.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] On-time updating of the IDS with the signature is a key aspect.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Anomaly-based intrusion detection systems were primarily introduced to detect unknown attacks, in part due to the rapid development of malware.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The basic approach is to use machine learning to create a model of trustworthy activity, and then compare new behavior against this model.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Since these models can be trained according to the applications and hardware configurations, machine learning based method has a better generalized property in comparison to traditional signature-based IDS.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Although this approach enables the detection of previously unknown attacks, it may suffer from false positives: previously unknown legitimate activity may also be classified as malicious.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Most of the existing IDSs suffer from the time-consuming during detection process that degrades the performance of IDSs.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Efficient feature selection algorithm makes the classification process used in detection more reliable.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Recent research has also explored deep learning approaches for anomaly-based intrusion detection, as these methods can learn complex traffic patterns and help identify previously unseen attacks more effectively.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] New types of what could be called anomaly-based intrusion detection systems are being viewed by Gartner as User and Entity Behavior Analytics (UEBA) (an evolution of the user behavior analytics category) and network traffic analysis (NTA).
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] In particular, NTA deals with malicious insiders as well as targeted external attacks that have compromised a user machine or account.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Gartner has noted that some organizations have opted for NTA over more traditional IDS.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Some systems may attempt to stop an intrusion attempt but this is neither required nor expected of a monitoring system.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Intrusion detection and prevention systems (IDPS) are primarily focused on identifying possible incidents, logging information about them, and reporting attempts.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] In addition, organizations use IDPS for other purposes, such as identifying problems with security policies, documenting existing threats and deterring individuals from violating security policies.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] IDPS have become a necessary addition to the security infrastructure of nearly every organization.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] IDPS typically record information related to observed events, notify security administrators of important observed events and produce reports.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Many IDPS can also respond to a detected threat by attempting to prevent it from succeeding.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] They use several response techniques, which involve the IDPS stopping the attack itself, changing the security environment (e.g. reconfiguring a firewall) or changing the attack's content.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Intrusion prevention systems are considered extensions of intrusion detection systems because they both monitor network traffic and/or system activities for malicious activity.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The main differences are, unlike intrusion detection systems, intrusion prevention systems are placed in-line and are able to actively prevent or block intrusions that are detected.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] IPS can take such actions as sending an alarm, dropping detected malicious packets, resetting a connection or blocking traffic from the offending IP address.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] An IPS also can correct cyclic redundancy check (CRC) errors, defragment packet streams, mitigate TCP sequencing issues, and clean up unwanted transport and network layer options.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] **Wireless intrusion prevention system (WIPS)**: monitor a wireless network for suspicious traffic by analyzing wireless networking protocols.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] **Network behavior analysis (NBA)**: examines network traffic to identify threats that generate unusual traffic flows, such as distributed denial of service (DDoS) attacks, certain forms of malware and policy violations.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] **Host-based intrusion prevention system (HIPS)**: an installed software package which monitors a single host for suspicious activity by analyzing events occurring within that host.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The majority of intrusion prevention systems utilize one of three detection methods: signature-based, statistical anomaly-based, and stateful protocol analysis.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] **Statistical anomaly-based detection**: An IDS which is anomaly-based will monitor network traffic and compare it against an established baseline.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The baseline will identify what is "normal" for that network – what sort of bandwidth is generally used and what protocols are used.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] It may however, raise a False Positive alarm for legitimate use of bandwidth if the baselines are not intelligently configured.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Ensemble models that use Matthews correlation co-efficient to identify unauthorized network traffic have obtained 99.73% accuracy.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] **Stateful protocol analysis detection**: This method identifies deviations of protocol states by comparing observed events with "pre-determined profiles of generally accepted definitions of benign activity".
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] While it is capable of knowing and tracing the protocol states, it requires significant resources.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The correct placement of intrusion detection systems is critical and varies depending on the network.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The most common placement is behind the firewall, on the edge of a network.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] This practice provides the IDS with high visibility of traffic entering your network and will not receive any traffic between users on the network.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The edge of the network is the point in which a network connects to the extranet.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] If an IDS is placed beyond a network's firewall, its main purpose would be to defend against noise from the internet but, more importantly, defend against common attacks, such as port scans and network mapper.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] An IDS in this position would monitor layers 4 through 7 of the OSI model and would be signature-based.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] This is a very useful practice, because rather than showing actual breaches into the network that made it through the firewall, attempted breaches will be shown which reduces the amount of false positives.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The IDS in this position also assists in decreasing the amount of time it takes to discover successful attacks against a network.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Sometimes an IDS with more advanced features will be integrated with a firewall in order to be able to intercept sophisticated attacks entering the network.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Examples of advanced features would include multiple security contexts in the routing level and bridging mode.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] All of this in turn potentially reduces cost and operational complexity.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Another option for IDS placement is within the actual network.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] These will reveal attacks or suspicious activity within the network.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Ignoring the security within a network can cause many problems, it will either allow users to bring about security risks or allow an attacker who has already broken into the network to roam around freely.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Intense intranet security makes it difficult for even those hackers within the network to maneuver around and escalate their privileges.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The earliest preliminary IDS concept was delineated in 1980 by James Anderson at the National Security Agency and consisted of a set of tools intended to help administrators review audit trails.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] User access logs, file access logs, and system event logs are examples of audit trails.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Fred Cohen noted in 1987 that it is impossible to detect an intrusion in every case, and that the resources needed to detect intrusions grow with the amount of usage.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Neumann, published a model of an IDS in 1986 that formed the basis for many systems today.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Her model used statistics for anomaly detection, and resulted in an early IDS at SRI International named the Intrusion Detection Expert System (IDES), which ran on Sun workstations and could consider both user and network level data.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] IDES had a dual approach with a rule-based Expert System to detect known types of intrusions plus a statistical anomaly detection component based on profiles of users, host systems, and target systems.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The author of "IDES: An Intelligent System for Detecting Intruders", Teresa F.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Lunt, proposed adding an artificial neural network as a third component.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] She said all three components could then report to a resolver.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] SRI followed IDES in 1993 with the Next-generation Intrusion Detection Expert System (NIDES).
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The Multics intrusion detection and alerting system (MIDAS), an expert system using P-BEST and Lisp, was developed in 1988 based on the work of Denning and Neumann.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Haystack was also developed in that year using statistics to reduce audit trails.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] In 1986 the National Security Agency started an IDS research transfer program under Rebecca Bace.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Bace later published the seminal text on the subject, *Intrusion Detection*, in 2000.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Wisdom & Sense (W&S) was a statistics-based anomaly detector developed in 1989 at the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] W&S created rules based on statistical analysis, and then used those rules for anomaly detection.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] In 1990, the Time-based Inductive Machine (TIM) did anomaly detection using inductive learning of sequential user patterns in Common Lisp on a VAX 3500 computer.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The Network Security Monitor (NSM) performed masking on access matrices for anomaly detection on a Sun-3/50 workstation.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The Information Security Officer's Assistant (ISOA) was a 1990 prototype that considered a variety of strategies including statistics, a profile checker, and an expert system.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] ComputerWatch at AT&T Bell Labs used statistics and rules for audit data reduction and intrusion detection.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Then, in 1991, researchers at the University of California, Davis created a prototype Distributed Intrusion Detection System (DIDS), which was also an expert system.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The Network Anomaly Detection and Intrusion Reporter (NADIR), also in 1991, was a prototype IDS developed at the Los Alamos National Laboratory's Integrated Computing Network (ICN), and was heavily influenced by the work of Denning and Lunt.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] NADIR used a statistics-based anomaly detector and an expert system.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory announced Bro in 1998, which used its own rule language for packet analysis from libpcap data.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Network Flight Recorder (NFR) in 1999 also used libpcap.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] APE was developed as a packet sniffer, also using libpcap, in November, 1998, and was renamed Snort one month later.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Snort has since become the world's largest used IDS/IPS system with over 300,000 active users.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] It can monitor both local systems, and remote capture points using the TZSP protocol.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The Audit Data Analysis and Mining (ADAM) IDS in 2001 used tcpdump to build profiles of rules for classifications.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] In 2003, Yongguang Zhang and Wenke Lee argue for the importance of IDS in networks with mobile nodes.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] In 2015, Viegas and his colleagues proposed an anomaly-based intrusion detection engine, aiming System-on-Chip (SoC) for applications in Internet of Things (IoT), for instance.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The proposal applies machine learning for anomaly detection, providing energy-efficiency to a Decision Tree, Naive-Bayes, and k-Nearest Neighbors classifiers implementation in an Atom CPU and its hardware-friendly implementation in a FPGA.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] In the literature, this was the first work that implement each classifier equivalently in software and hardware and measures its energy consumption on both.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Additionally, it was the first time that was measured the energy consumption for extracting each features used to make the network packet classification, implemented in software and hardware.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] Several regulatory frameworks require or recommend intrusion detection capabilities as part of information security compliance.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] In the United States, the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) Security Rule requires covered entities to implement procedures for monitoring log-in attempts and reporting discrepancies as part of their information system activity review.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The December 2024 Notice of proposed rulemaking (NPRM) to overhaul the HIPAA Security Rule would explicitly mandate deployment of intrusion detection and intrusion prevention systems, along with continuous monitoring of all information systems containing electronic protected health information.
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) requires the use of intrusion detection or intrusion prevention techniques to detect or prevent intrusions into networks handling cardholder data (Requirement 11.5).
[src:deception-technology-deep/intrusion-detection-system] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP 800-53 includes the SI-4 (Information System Monitoring) control family, which specifies intrusion detection as a core capability for federal information systems.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] A **tarpit** is a service on a computer system (usually a server) that purposely delays incoming connections.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] The technique was developed as a defense against spam and computer worms.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] The idea is that network abuses such as spamming or broad scanning are less effective, and therefore less attractive, if they take too long.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] The concept is analogous with a tar pit, in which animals can get bogged down and slowly sink under the surface, like in a swamp.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] By 2000, SMTP e-mail servers, such as Postfix, had rate limiting options that were referred to as tarpitting by the community.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] In 2001, following the Code Red worm, Tom Liston developed a network tarpitting program *LaBrea*.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] It could use a single computer to operate a tarpit on all unused addresses in a network.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] One of the possible avenues that were considered to battle bulk-spam at one time, was to mandate a small fee for every submitted mail.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] By introducing such artificial cost, with negligible impact on legitimate use as long as the fee is small enough, automated mass-scale spam would instantly become unattractive.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] Tarpitting could be seen as a similar (but technically much less complex) approach, where the cost for the spammer would be measured in terms of time and efficiency rather than money.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] Authentication procedures increase response times as users attempt invalid passwords.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] However, server-to-server SMTP transfers, which is where spam is injected, require no authentication.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] Various methods have been discussed and implemented for SMTP tarpits, systems that plug into the Mail Transfer Agent (MTA, i.e. the mail server software) or sit in front of it as a proxy.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] One method increases transfer time for all mails by a few seconds by delaying the initial greeting message ("greet delay").
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] The idea is that it will not matter if a legitimate mail takes a little longer to deliver, but due to the high volume, it will make a difference for spammers.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] The downside of this is that mailing lists and other legitimate mass-mailings will have to be explicitly whitelisted or they will suffer, too.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] Some email systems, such as sendmail 8.13+, implement a stronger form of greet delay.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] This form pauses when the connection is first established and listens for traffic.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] If it detects any traffic prior to its own greeting (in violation of RFC 2821) it closes the connection.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] Since many spammers do not write their SMTP implementations to the specification, this can reduce the number of incoming spam messages.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] Another method is to delay only known spammers, e.g. by using a blacklist (see Spamming, DNSBL).
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] OpenBSD has integrated this method into their core system since OpenBSD 3.3, with a special-purpose daemon (spamd) and functionality in the firewall (pf) to redirect known spammers to this tarpit.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] MS Exchange can tarpit senders who send to an invalid address.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] Exchange can do this because the SMTP connector is connected to the authentication system.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] A more subtle idea is greylisting, which, in simple terms, rejects the first connection attempt from any previously unseen IP address.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] The assumption is that most spammers make only one connection attempt (or a few attempts over a short period of time) to send each message, whereas legitimate mail delivery systems will keep retrying over a longer period.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] After they retry, they will eventually be allowed in without any further impediments.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] Finally, a more elaborate method tries to glue tarpits and filtering software together, by filtering e-mail in realtime, while it is being transmitted, and adding delays to the communication in response to the filter's "spam likeliness" indicator.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] For example, the spam filter would make a "guess" after each line or after every x bytes received as to how likely this message is going to be spam.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] The more likely this is, the more the MTA will delay the transmission.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] SMTP consists of requests, which are mostly four-letter words such as MAIL, and replies, which are (minimally) three-digit numbers.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] In the last line of the reply, the number is followed by a space; in the preceding lines it is followed by a hyphen.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] The tarpit waits fifteen or more seconds between lines (long delays are allowed in SMTP, as humans sometimes send mail manually to test mail servers).
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] This ties up the SMTP sending process on the spammer's computer so as to limit the amount of spam it can send.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] A machine running the LaBrea tarpit listens for Address Resolution Protocol requests that go unanswered (indicating unused addresses), then replies to those requests, receives the initial SYN packet of the scanner and sends a SYN/ACK in response.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] It does not open a socket or prepare a connection, in fact it can forget all about the connection after sending the SYN/ACK.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] However, the remote site sends its ACK (which gets ignored) and believes the 3-way-handshake to be complete.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] Then it starts to send data, which never reaches a destination.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] The connection will time out after a while, but since the system believes it is dealing with a live (established) connection, it is conservative in timing it out and will instead try to retransmit, back-off, retransmit, etc. for quite a while.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] The Linux kernel can now be patched to allow tarpitting of incoming connections instead of the more usual dropping of packets.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] This is implemented in iptables by the addition of a TARPIT target.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] The same packet inspection and matching features can be applied to tarpit targets as are applied to other targets.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] A server can determine that a given mail message is spam, e.g. because it was addressed to a spam trap, or after trusted users' reports.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] The server may decide that the IP address responsible for submitting the message deserves tarpitting.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] Cross-checking against available DNSBLs can help to avoid including innocent forwarders in the tarpit database.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] A daemon exploiting Linux libipq can then check the remote address of incoming SMTP connections against that database.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] SpamCannibal is a GPL software designed around this idea; Stockade is a similar project implemented using FreeBSD ipfirewall.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] One advantage of tarpitting at the IP level is that regular TCP connections handled by an MTA are *stateful*.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] That is, although the MTA doesn't use much CPU while it sleeps, it still uses the amount of memory required to hold the state of each connection.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] On the opposite, LaBrea-style tarpitting is *stateless*, thus gaining the advantage of a reduced cost against the spammer's box.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] However, making use of botnets, spammers can externalize most of their computer-resource costs.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] Tarpits can also be used to trap artificial intelligence scrapers.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] In this model, an endpoint is set up that serves incoherent text generated with a Markov chain to AI scrapers to poison their dataset.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] The URL is blacklisted in robots.txt to not catch legitimate scrapers.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] It is known that a tarpitted connection may generate a significant amount of traffic towards the receiver, because the sender considers the connection as established and tries to send (and then retransmit) actual data.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] In practice, given current average computer botnet size, a more reasonable solution will be to drop suspicious traffic completely, without tarpitting.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] This way, only TCP SYN segments will be retransmitted, not the whole HTTP or HTTPS requests.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] As well as MS Exchange, there have been two other successful commercial implementations of the tar pit idea.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] The first was developed by TurnTide, a Philadelphia-based startup company, which was acquired by Symantec in 2004 for $28 million in cash.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] The TurnTide Anti Spam Router contains a modified Linux kernel which allows it to play various tricks with TCP traffic, such as varying the TCP window size.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] By grouping various email senders into different traffic classes and limiting the bandwidth for each class, the amount of abusive traffic is reduced – particularly when the abusive traffic is coming from single sources which are easily identified by their high traffic volume.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] After the Symantec acquisition, a Canadian startup company called MailChannels released their "Traffic Control" software, which uses a slightly different approach to achieve similar results.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] Traffic Control is a semi-realtime SMTP proxy.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] Unlike the TurnTide appliance, which applies traffic shaping at the network layer, Traffic Control applies traffic shaping to individual senders at the application layer.
[src:deception-technology-deep/tarpit-networking] This approach results in a somewhat more effective handling of spam traffic originating from botnets because it allows the software to slow traffic from individual spam zombies, rather than requiring zombie traffic to be aggregated into a class.
